Text: For this last blog post for project three, I'd like to muse a bit on why I often feel like I'm struggling to make our team's application work, and how this whole project has really brought home the importance of design patterns and principles.
I've always found the Unix-philosophy of "do one thing and do it well" beneficial.
Your code focuses on one task and it allows each individual with different strengths to work on their preferred module.
It also forces you to break down your task into smaller ones until it's no longer practical to do so.
And having distinct, manageable tasks are key to productivity.

Plus, if your programs and functions are functional, meaning they always return X if Y is given as parameter and has no side effect, it makes it a lot easier to test, maintain, debug and generally reason about.
Against that background, our choice of framework (Model - View - View Model) is designed to do that.
The model mirrors a table in the database, and only contains data definition.
The view only contains markup and styling.
The View Model handles the data binding, which basically means what properties of the Model the View should display and which component should do so.
So in essence designers can work on the overall look, while members with a more logical leaning can focus on the business logic.
And we did kind of achieve that separation of concern during the last 2 or 3 weeks.
But another equally important factor that affects how we plan our code is user experience and expectations.
What this means is that our users prefer to do everything in one place, from one page, and reporting nature of the application also means that our models are often mixed up together in one place.

The same view is then reused for all CRUD operations which often involve 2 or 3 models due to the interconnected nature of the system, and it's really hard to make it all work, and it feels really discouraging at times as the application is slow due to our hosted database and the obscure nature of data binding debugging, which often runs but doesn't do what you want and so there's no error message to guide you.
But still, I did manage to somewhat follow what I think it's good practices in other places.
To reduce code duplication, I wrote certain base classes, generics, and interfaces for our models and database services.
The folders clearly group modules based on their tasks, and you wouldn't know how much of a mess everything is at first glance.
There were definitely times where I felt I should have reflected on how much impact our user-friendly designs would have on our developer experience, or pushed for a more single-purpose design.
But the power dynamics is hard to navigate, with Bibi being the obvious experienced lead who seems to make it work regardless, while Gogo and Susu always have UX as their first priorities.
In the end I felt I've pulled my weight where I needed to, and I learned a lot so it's okay.
For this week, besides my portfolio, I'll try to finish my two remaining features and call it done.
It's time for me to move on, and I really want to apply what I've learnt by starting afresh on my next project.
Overall
